      <h2>Blade Selection for Tree Limbing</h2>
      <p>The saw is only half the equation. For tree limbing and storm cleanup, use an 8-inch or 12-inch pruning blade with 4 to 6 teeth per inch. The wide tooth spacing clears wet sawdust efficiently, preventing the blade from binding in green wood. Bi-metal pruning blades resist heat buildup during extended cuts, while carbide-grit blades survive contact with bark-embedded rocks and dirt on storm-felled trees. For branches over 6 inches thick, use a pruning blade with a tapered tip that starts the cut without kickback and transitions to aggressive cutting through the branch width. Arborists typically carry three blade types: a pruning blade for green limbs, a demolition blade for nail-embedded lumber, and a carbide blade for roots and abrasive material.</p>

      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>The right reciprocating saw for tree work depends on how often you make the cut. For tree service crews and arborists who limb and prune daily, the Milwaukee M18 FUEL Sawzall offers the best combination of battery runtime, stroke length, and anti-vibration for sustained overhead work. Its 3,800-plus five-star ratings reflect field performance across arborist, landscaping, and storm restoration contractors. For contractors who need unlimited runtime during multi-day storm cleanup operations, the DEWALT DW304 corded model remains the benchmark for sustained heavy cutting through branches of any size. For homeowners and light contractors who prune seasonally, the Ryobi P516 provides adequate cutting power at the lowest platform entry cost. Match the saw to the frequency of the work, pair it with quality pruning blades, and it will handle everything from a single broken branch to a full property storm restoration.</p>

